Read-only analysis complete. The implementable lower-crate inversion seam should live in the already-neutral lower crate `crates/jcode-core/src/activity.rs`, exposed as `pub mod activity;` from `crates/jcode-core/src/lib.rs`. Rationale: `jcode-app-core` already depends on `jcode-core` and `jcode-base` (`crates/jcode-app-core/Cargo.toml:85-89`), while `jcode-base` already depends on `jcode-core` (`crates/jcode-base/Cargo.toml:103-104`) and does not depend on `jcode-app-core` (`crates/jcode-base/Cargo.toml:7-12`, `crates/jcode-app-core/src/lib.rs:12-24`). Therefore a trait/type seam in `jcode-core` lets lower `jcode-base` code acquire leases without importing server-local app-core code, avoiding the dependency cycle identified by the review.

Review/design driver: the architecture critique states that the proposed authorities were in `crates/jcode-app-core/src/server/`, but production MCP lives in lower `jcode-base` (`docs/fork/ideal-base/reviews/F01-architecture-critique.md:55-66`). It explicitly requires an implementable inversion seam, suggesting either a lower neutral process-activity interface/guard or injected lease callback/trait into `McpManager` and `BackgroundTaskManager` (`docs/fork/ideal-base/reviews/F01-architecture-critique.md:84-89`). The same critique records the unresolved coverage gap for non-detached background tasks and MCP calls (`docs/fork/ideal-base/reviews/F01-architecture-critique.md:278-280`).

Current source confirms all three needed lower-code call paths. Pooled MCP: `McpTool::execute` calls `McpManager::call_tool` (`crates/jcode-base/src/mcp/tool.rs:49-58`). `McpManager` stores shared-pool handles and owned clients (`crates/jcode-base/src/mcp/manager.rs:48-54`), and its `call_tool` fast paths call pooled `McpHandle::call_tool` (`crates/jcode-base/src/mcp/manager.rs:348-355`) and owned `McpClient::call_tool` (`crates/jcode-base/src/mcp/manager.rs:357-364`), with connect-on-first-call retry paths for both (`crates/jcode-base/src/mcp/manager.rs:367-388`). `SharedMcpPool::call_tool` is also public and directly calls a handle (`crates/jcode-base/src/mcp/pool.rs:231-243`). Per-session MCP: `McpManager` comments and fields explicitly cover non-shared per-session clients (`crates/jcode-base/src/mcp/manager.rs:1-5`, `crates/jcode-base/src/mcp/manager.rs:44-54`), and connection creates owned clients under `OwnedChildPermit` (`crates/jcode-base/src/mcp/manager.rs:159-184`, `crates/jcode-base/src/mcp/manager.rs:242-257`). Background tasks: `BackgroundTaskManager` lives in `jcode-base` (`crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:35-39`), writes non-detached Running status files with owner metadata (`crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:439-459`, `crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:642-657`), tracks live tasks in an in-memory map (`crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:584-600`, `crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:787-803`), and reconciles orphaned non-detached tasks after crash/reload because their futures die with the process (`crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:248-281`, `crates/jcode-app-core/src/server.rs:1171-1185`). Detached background tasks must not lease because the design explicitly excludes them (`docs/fork/ideal-base/evidence/F01/design.md:62-65`) and `register_detached_task` marks `detached: true` (`crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:357-380`).

Proposed lower API in `crates/jcode-core/src/activity.rs`:

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, Hash, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub enum ActivityClass {
    ClientConnection,
    ProviderTurn,
    HeadlessTurn,
    DebugJob,
    BackgroundTask,
    McpCall,
    SwarmWaiter,
    ScheduledDelivery,
    ReloadHandoff,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct ActivityLeaseRequest {
    pub class: ActivityClass,
    pub owner: Option<String>,     // session id, task id, server name, etc.
    pub label: String,             // human/debug label
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, Hash)]
pub struct ActivityLeaseToken(pub u64);

#[derive(Debug, Clone, PartialEq, Eq)]
pub enum ActivityLeaseError {
    ShuttingDown { reason: String },
    CapacityExceeded { class: ActivityClass, limit: usize },
}

pub trait ActivityLeaseAuthority: Send + Sync + 'static {
    fn acquire(&self, request: ActivityLeaseRequest) -> Result<ActivityLeaseToken, ActivityLeaseError>;
    fn release(&self, token: ActivityLeaseToken);
    fn snapshot(&self) -> ActivityLeaseSnapshot;
}

pub struct ActivityLeaseGuard {
    authority: Option<std::sync::Arc<dyn ActivityLeaseAuthority>>,
    token: ActivityLeaseToken,
}

impl ActivityLeaseGuard {
    pub fn acquire(authority: &std::sync::Arc<dyn ActivityLeaseAuthority>, request: ActivityLeaseRequest)
        -> Result<Self, ActivityLeaseError>;
}
impl Drop for ActivityLeaseGuard { /* release token synchronously */ }

pub fn noop_activity_authority() -> std::sync::Arc<dyn ActivityLeaseAuthority>;
```

`ActivityLeaseAuthority` must be synchronous and `std`-only because release happens from `Drop`; app-core can implement it with a `std::sync::Mutex<LeaseTable>`. `ActivityLeaseGuard` mirrors the existing RAII pattern for `OwnedChildPermit`, which already acquires before spawning and releases on drop (`crates/jcode-base/src/mcp/client.rs:36-60`). `ActivityLeaseError` gives shutdown/capacity refusal semantics without making lower crates depend on `anyhow` or server types.

Concrete app-core implementation placement: `crates/jcode-app-core/src/server/activity.rs` implements `ServerActivityLeaseAuthority` over the pure lease table described by the design (`docs/fork/ideal-base/evidence/F01/design.md:99-138`). The `Server` owns `Arc<ServerActivityLeaseAuthority>` and passes it down by trait object. Idle decisions then require zero clients and zero active leases, matching A1 (`docs/fork/ideal-base/ACCEPTANCE_STANDARD.md:17-23`) instead of today’s client-count-only predicate (`crates/jcode-app-core/src/server/lifecycle.rs:90-96`, `crates/jcode-app-core/src/server/lifecycle.rs:159-178`).

MCP wiring:
1. Add `activity: Arc<dyn ActivityLeaseAuthority>` to `McpManager` and `SharedMcpPool`, with existing constructors (`new`, `with_config`, `from_default_config`) defaulting to `noop_activity_authority()` for tests/backcompat.
2. Add `_with_activity` constructors: `McpManager::with_shared_pool_for_dir_and_activity(pool, session_id, project_dir, activity)`, `McpManager::with_config_and_activity(config, activity)`, and `SharedMcpPool::from_default_config_with_activity(activity)`.
3. In `McpManager::call_tool`, acquire one `ActivityClass::McpCall` guard at entry before either pooled or owned path, labeled with `session_id`, `server`, and `tool`; hold through the awaited handle/client call. This single guard covers pooled fast path (`manager.rs:348-355`), owned fast path (`manager.rs:357-364`), and connect-on-first-call retry paths (`manager.rs:367-388`).
4. Also wrap public `SharedMcpPool::call_tool` (`crates/jcode-base/src/mcp/pool.rs:231-243`) so any direct lower-level caller is covered.
5. App-core composition point: `get_shared_mcp_pool` currently constructs `SharedMcpPool::from_default_config()` (`crates/jcode-app-core/src/server/util.rs:39-43`); change it to accept/pass the server authority. `Registry::register_mcp_tools_for_dir` currently constructs `McpManager::with_shared_pool_for_dir(...)` or `McpManager::new()` (`crates/jcode-app-core/src/tool/mod.rs:758-778`); change it to take an activity authority and use the new constructors. The server/headless call sites already pass shared pools into registration (`crates/jcode-app-core/src/server.rs:793-800`, plus runtime call sites noted by `crates/jcode-app-core/src/server/runtime.rs:336` and `:391` from grep), so this is an explicit composition-root injection, not a dependency inversion violation.

Background task wiring:
1. Add `activity: Arc<dyn ActivityLeaseAuthority>` to `BackgroundTaskManager`; keep `with_output_dir` and `new/global` defaulting to noop for tests/backcompat, plus `with_output_dir_and_activity` for server-owned managers. If global singleton use must remain, add a lower-crate-safe `set_activity_authority_for_process(activity)` before first non-detached spawn, or prefer passing a manager handle through app-core where feasible.
2. Acquire `ActivityClass::BackgroundTask` only for non-detached spawns/adoptions. The acquisition point should be before writing the initial non-detached Running status (`crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:439-459` and `crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:642-657`), labeled by `task_id`, `session_id`, and `tool_name` from `TaskStatusFile` fields (`crates/jcode-base/src/background/model.rs:44-83`).
3. Move the guard into the wrapper future or the `RunningTask` entry. Holding it in the wrapper future guarantees release on normal completion and on abort because `cancel_with_grace` aborts the handle (`crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:1117-1127`); holding it in `RunningTask` also releases on map removal after terminal status write (`crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:543-552`, `crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:754-758`). Prefer wrapper-future ownership plus optional token/debug label in `RunningTask`.
4. Do not acquire leases for detached tasks because the design says detached background tasks outlive the daemon by design (`docs/fork/ideal-base/evidence/F01/design.md:62-65`), and detached status reconciliation follows real pid liveness (`crates/jcode-base/src/background.rs:139-180`).
5. For shutdown refusal, add `try_spawn_with_notify` / `try_adopt_with_options` returning `Result<BackgroundTaskInfo, ActivityLeaseError>` and migrate app-core call sites; existing non-try methods can remain as noop-authority-compatible adapters during transition.

Dependency direction after change: `jcode-core` defines only trait/types/RAII guard; `jcode-base` depends on `jcode-core` and calls only `Arc<dyn ActivityLeaseAuthority>`; `jcode-app-core` depends on both, implements the concrete table/coordinator integration, and injects the authority when constructing `SharedMcpPool`, `McpManager`, and non-detached `BackgroundTaskManager`. No `jcode-base -> jcode-app-core` dependency is introduced, resolving the review’s cycle concern.

Tests to add when implementing: (1) pure `jcode-core`/app-core lease table RAII drop/release and refusal tests; (2) MCP unit tests with a fake authority proving `McpManager::call_tool` acquires/releases once for pooled fast path, owned fast path, and connect-on-first-call path; (3) `SharedMcpPool::call_tool` direct wrapper test; (4) background manager tests proving non-detached spawn/adopt holds one lease until completion/cancel and detached registration holds none; (5) server lifecycle test proving idle does not exit while fake MCP/background lease is active and exits after release plus timeout, matching A1.
